message.content: We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The obturator nerve innervates the adductor longus, adductor brevis, adductor magnus, and gracilis muscles. Therefore, the function of the adductor longus muscle is most likely to be affected following the procedure. Tensor fascia latae is innervated by the superior gluteal nerve, transversus abdominis by the thoracoabdominal nerves, and semitendinosus by the tibial division of the sciatic nerve, which are not related to the obturator nerve.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The obturator nerve supplies the adductor longus muscle, making it the most likely muscle to be affected by an obturator nerve injury during the procedure. The other options are not innervated by the obturator nerve.

We refer to Wikipedia articles on medicine for help. The obturator nerve supplies the adductor longus muscle, so injuring the nerve can cause weakness or paralysis of this muscle. Tensor fascia latae is supplied by the superior gluteal nerve, transversus abdominis is supplied by the lower intercostal nerves and iliohypogastric and ilioinguinal nerves, and semitendinosus is supplied by the tibial division of the sciatic nerve, so they are not likely to be affected by an injury to the obturator nerve.

The obturator nerve innervates the adductor longus, adductor brevis, adductor magnus, gracilis, pectineus, and obturator externus muscles, so the most likely muscle to be affected following the procedure is the adductor longus. Tensor fascia latae is innervated by the superior gluteal nerve, transversus abdominis by the thoracoabdominal nerves, and semitendinosus by the tibial branch of the sciatic nerve.

Therefore, if the nerve is injured during the sling surgery, the adductor longus muscle is most likely to be affected. Tensor fascia latae is innervated by the superior gluteal nerve, transversus abdominis is innervated by the thoracoabdominal nerves, and semitendinosus is innervated by the tibial nerve, so their function would not be affected by an injury to the obturator nerve.
